# arvo-bits-contracts. Design

The bit-level trait declarations. Every trait here is `pub const trait`.
Default-method bodies reference `Bits<N, S>` and the bare primitive
containers; consumer call sites pull this crate to bind to the trait
surface, then reach the concrete impls in `arvo-bits` via blanket
dispatch. `#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-transparent`, `arvo-strategy`, `arvo-storage`.

## HasBitWidth

```rust
pub const trait HasBitWidth {
    const WIDTH: USize;
}
```

How many logical bits a type occupies. Renamed from `BitWidth` per
round 202604271346 to free that name for the `Width` newtype in
`arvo-storage`. Const trait so `T::WIDTH` works in const fn bodies
under generic-T.

## BitAccess

```rust
pub const trait BitAccess: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn bit(self, idx: USize) -> Bool;
    fn with_bit_set(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn with_bit_cleared(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn with_bit_toggled(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
}
```

Individual bit manipulation. Functional style, no mutation. `idx` is
from LSB.

## BitSequence

```rust
pub const trait BitSequence: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn trailing_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn leading_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn count_ones(self) -> USize;
    fn count_zeros(self) -> USize;
    fn is_zero(self) -> Bool;
}
```

Scanning and counting. Maps to hardware intrinsics (`cttz`, `ctlz`,
`popcnt`). The primitives that mask iteration uses internally.

## BitLogic

```rust
pub const trait BitLogic: HasBitWidth + Copy {
    fn bitor(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn bitand(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn bitnot(self) -> Self;
    fn bitxor(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn shl(self, n: USize) -> Self;
    fn shr(self, n: USize) -> Self;
    fn clear_lowest_set_bit(self) -> Self
    where
        Self: BitAccess + BitSequence;
}
```

Whole-word bitwise logic. Single-instruction on the backing
primitive. Hot-only surface (other strategies' wider containers make
whole-word ops meaningless at the logical-width level).

`clear_lowest_set_bit` has a default body via `BitSequence` +
`BitAccess`; concrete types override with the BLSR-equivalent fast
path.

## BitPrim family

```rust
pub const trait BitPrim: Copy + ConstParamTy_ + ... {
    // primitive-bridge methods on bare u8/u16/u32/u64
}

pub const trait UBitContainer<const N: u8> {
    type Container: BitPrim;
}

pub const trait IBitContainer<const N: u8> {
    type Container: BitPrim;
}
```

The primitive-bridge family. `BitPrim` is the sealed surface that
`u8`, `u16`, `u32`, `u64` (and signed counterparts) implement, used
by blanket impls in `arvo-bits` to delegate from
`Bits<N, S>::to_raw()` to the primitive's bit method, then
`Bits::from_raw(...)` wraps the result. Const trait throughout.

